              <tr><td><strong>Co-occurrence</strong></td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>Brand and keyword appear together</td><td>Consistent messaging around a topic</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Brand mention</strong></td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>Brand is notable enough to be discussed</td><td>PR, thought leadership, journalism</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Anchor text</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Specific keywords describe a linked URL</td><td>Editorial link contexts</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real co-citation examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Listicle inclusion</h3>
        <p>An industry publication publishes "10 SEO tools worth your budget in 2026" and lists <em>theStacc</em>, <em>Semrush</em>, <em>Ahrefs</em>, and <em>Moz</em> — none linked. Every future reader parses those four names as belonging to the same cluster. Do this 100 times across the web and your brand starts surfacing in AI-answer sets alongside those legacy names.</p>

        <h3>2. Expert-quote roundup</h3>
        <p>A journalist writes a round-up on "how CMOs pick SEO agencies" and quotes marketers from theStacc alongside marketers from three national agencies. All four brands are named without links. The co-citation reinforces theStacc as adjacent to those agencies in the entity graph.</p>

        <h3>3. Comparison table on a blog</h3>
        <p>A publisher builds a side-by-side comparison table listing theStacc, Semrush, and Ahrefs across features. Even if the table only links to Semrush and Ahrefs, mentioning theStacc in the same table structure creates a strong co-citation signal.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Co-citation vs backlink — where each wins</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Co-citation strengths</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Cheaper to earn than editorial backlinks</li>
              <li>Not subject to Google's link-spam updates</li>
              <li>Feeds entity graph and AI-answer selection</li>
              <li>Compounds without technical fragility</li>
              <li>Impossible for competitors to disavow away</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Backlink strengths</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Passes explicit PageRank</li>
              <li>Anchor text sends direct topical relevance</li>
              <li>Drives referral traffic directly</li>
              <li>Measurable in tools like Ahrefs and Search Console</li>
              <li>Still the strongest single ranking factor for competitive queries</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>You want both. Backlinks build authority, co-citations build the entity neighbourhood that determines which queries you show up for.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 co-citation best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Get listed in "best X for Y" roundups.</strong> Reach out to publications already ranking for the exact query you want to be considered for.</li>
          <li><strong>Participate in expert-quote posts.</strong> Sites like HARO, Featured, and Qwoted publish roundups that co-cite you with well-known peers automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Sponsor or contribute to industry reports.</strong> Reports that group brands into categories create thousands of durable co-citation instances.</li>
          <li><strong>Target competitor-mention sources.</strong> Find every article that mentions your competitors without linking. Ask to be added — many publishers will oblige for a genuinely relevant addition.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish comparison content yourself.</strong> Your own "theStacc vs Semrush" post gets referenced by others, seeding co-citations of its own.</li>
          <li><strong>Sponsor podcasts and webinars that already cover competitors.</strong> Podcast show notes with your brand mentioned alongside a competitor is high-value structured co-citation.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — chasing volume over quality</div>
          <p>1,000 co-citations from low-authority scraper sites do nothing. 20 co-citations in <em>Search Engine Land</em>, <em>Marketing Week</em>, and <em>HubSpot's blog</em> move the entity needle massively. Prioritise where the mention appears, not how many mentions exist.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common co-citation mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring unlinked mentions.</strong> Every unlinked mention is a co-citation opportunity. Use tools like Ahrefs Alerts or Mention to monitor and pursue link additions where appropriate.</li>
          <li><strong>Getting cited alongside unrelated brands.</strong> If your SEO SaaS is cited alongside a coffee shop, the entity graph gets muddled. Chase relevant neighbourhoods only.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming co-citation replaces links.</strong> It does not. It complements them.</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking mentions.</strong> Without monitoring, you cannot measure or optimise the strategy.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying mentions in low-authority PBNs.</strong> Purchased co-citations from spammy sources can look like unnatural patterns to Google's spam classifiers.</li>
        </ul>

